data.name: pictureBox6.ToolTip
data.value:
All start locations will be picked in-order from top to bottom and Corrade will try each one in turn if login failed at the previous location.
This is the start location of Corrade. Valid values are: - home, - last
or a string such as:
Puguet Sound/128/152/17

data.name: pictureBox92.ToolTip
data.value:
You can set a master password here that, when sent from scripts, will allow you to control any group managed by Corrade. To use this feature, you would set a password here and then send commands to your Corrade as usual but instead of sending the group password, you would send the password you set here.
The password you set here cannot and should not be identical to any password of any configured group.
This setting is very dangerous because if this password is compromised by one of your groups - for instance, some group with "system" permission that can read the configuration file, then that group will be able to control any other group.

data.name: pictureBox81.ToolTip
data.value: Corrade can send certain notifications (such as alerts, group messages, etc...) to primitives that request them. Note that you should try to enable only the notifcations that you plan to use and that enabling a large amount of notifications that you never use will just slow Corrade down.

data.name: pictureBox80.ToolTip
data.value: These controls grant access to Corrade's more intimate functions, such as teleporting users, Corrade's money stash or movement. Be sparing in permissions that are never needed by your projects and pay particular attention to the "execute", "configuration", "economy" and "system" since they will allow scripts to manipulate some core features of the account that Corrade is using to connect to the grid.

data.name: pictureBox21.ToolTip
data.value: The AIML component will enable the "ai" command which will make it possible for Corrade to process incoming messages through the SIML component. Unless you are planning to use AI, you can leave this option off and spare a lot of RAM since this option tends to use ~50MiB.

data.name: pictureBox96.ToolTip
data.value:
This URL should point to the selected Corrade peer's HTTP server prefix.
For instance, to synchronize with a remote Corrade bot with the IP address 192.168.1.58 that has a HTTP prefix:
https://+:8080
you would enter the URL on your bot in the text box as:
https://192.168.1.58:8080
The "+" sign in the prefix means that the selected peer is listening on all interfaces. However, you should make sure that you are able to connect to at least one of those interfaces - in this example 192.168.1.58.

data.name: pictureBox95.ToolTip
data.value:
A Corrade horde will synchronize data, such as cache items, mutes, and so on, amongst various Corrade instances. This means that whenever a cache object is added, Corrade will distribute that object to other Corrade bots on the network.
In order to use the Corrade horde, the Corrade HTTP server must be running (configurable in the HTTP tab), and then horde peer URLs have to be added.
After that you can use the selector on the same tab in order to select with which assets you want your Corrade to participate in the horde with.
Note that the authentication is basic such that you should make it good practice to not add any non-HTTPs horde peer URLs and that you should run your HTTP server over the HTTPS protocol instead of HTTP.

data.name: pictureBox102.ToolTip
data.value:
This is an unique shared secret between your Corrade and the selected Corrade in the horde. As the name implies, this secret should be only between your Corrade and only one Corrade in the horde list, thus being unique.
This shared secret should be negotiated between you, as the Corrade owner and owner of the selected Corrade in the horde and kept secret between you two.
You can also press the generator button and a shared secret will be generated for you. You will then have to tell the owner of the other Corrade in the horde that you want this to be the secret between your bots.

data.name: pictureBox17.ToolTip
data.value: The input filters will be crossed on every message in- order from top to bottom. You can chain several input filters here as you wish and Corrade will run them all in sequence when it receives a message.

data.name: pictureBox88.ToolTip
data.value:
The key to use for AES - the length has to be either:
- 128b / 16B / 16 characters - 192b / 24B / 24 characters - 256b / 32B / 32 characters
or the configurator will not accept to set the value.

data.name: pictureBox84.ToolTip
data.value:
The notifications that are generated by Corrade can be retrieved through TCP by connecting to the configured address and port and requesting a type of notification.
Contrasted with notifications posted through callbacks, getting notifications through the TCP server requires a stateful and persistent connection and is recommended in cases where it is impossible for Corrade to post-back.

data.name: pictureBox85.ToolTip
data.value: This represents the IP address on which Corrade listens on for connecting clients requesting notifications over TCP. The default assumed value is 0.0.0.0 which will make Corrade bind to all adapters that it can and listen to all connecting clients.

data.name: pictureBox31.ToolTip
data.value: Whether to use the Naggle algorithm for callbacks and notifications. If you are on a slow network, enable this - otherwise, make sure to disable it since it will just slow down Corrade's connection.

data.name: pictureBox29.ToolTip
data.value: Second Life uses the MAC address of the bound network interface and the first hard-drive identifier in order to construct a hash that is sent to the grid to identify you. You can spoof this hash by setting a the first hard drive identifier here to any value.

data.name: pictureBox28.ToolTip
data.value: Second Life uses the MAC address of the bound network interface and the first hard-drive identifier in order to construct a hash that is sent to the grid to identify you. You can spoof this hash by setting a the network card MAC component here to any value.

data.name: pictureBox51.ToolTip
data.value: This setting controls how often (in milliseconds) should command schedules be checked. Note that you are most likely not running a real-time operating system such that you should keep this value to a sane setting such as 1 second (1000ms). Any schedules that are overdue will run on the next pass after this interval.

data.name: pictureBox42.ToolTip
data.value: The interval with which to track group membership events (agent joined, agent left group) for the membership notification. These scans can take some processing power since Corrade has to compare large sets for each group to find leaving and joining agents.

data.name: pictureBox40.ToolTip
data.value: The range in meters that Corrade will be able to spot agents, objects, simulators, etc... Setting this value too large will make Corrade connect to neighboring simulators as well. It is a good idea to leave this value small enough or the requirements will be greater in case Corrade must connect to neighboring regions.
